abstract: Proposals from Elizabeth Warren and Bernie Sanders have raised concerns from economists and business leaders who fear the plans would sap economic growth.
snippet: Proposals from Elizabeth Warren and Bernie Sanders have raised concerns from economists and business leaders who fear the plans would sap economic growth.
lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — Progressive Democrats are advocating the most drastic shift in tax policy in over a century as they look to redistribute wealth and chip away at the economic power of the superrich with new taxes that could fundamentally reshape the United States economy.

abstract: Democrats have moved left, but the party’s rank and file typically side with establishment favorites.
snippet: Democrats have moved left, but the party’s rank and file typically side with establishment favorites.
lead_paragraph: Elizabeth Warren is gaining. She has breached 20 percent of the vote in recent national surveys and might hold a narrow lead in Iowa and New Hampshire. The prediction markets now consider her a clear favorite to win the nomination. It can be hard to see how her Democratic rivals will attack or stop her.

abstract: How the MSNBC host staked her show on Trump — and won the largest and most obsessive audience of her career.
snippet: How the MSNBC host staked her show on Trump — and won the largest and most obsessive audience of her career.
lead_paragraph: Rachel Maddow was trying to get to work. She only had to get from the glass door of her doctor’s office to the tinted-windowed S.U.V. that was idling at the curb, waiting to spirit her to 30 Rockefeller Plaza, but there was a hitch. Maddow had torn three ligaments in her left ankle — fishing accident — and one of those ligaments ripped off a piece of her bone, so now she was lumbering toward the sidewalk, her foot strapped into a boot, her lanky body bent over crutches that creaked and boomed with every hit to the sidewalk. In Manhattan, this had the effect of a kind of ritualistic drumbeat, alerting every liberal within earshot to her presence.

headline_main: The Shark-Infested Waters of Trump’s Tweet-Filled Weekend

abstract: Don’t rush the inquiry, and make it about more than Trump’s Ukraine scandal.
snippet: Don’t rush the inquiry, and make it about more than Trump’s Ukraine scandal.
lead_paragraph: House Democratic leaders, following frustrated efforts to hold President Trump to account, understandably want to strike quickly to impeach him on the grounds of one extremely serious issue: his pressuring the president of Ukraine to get the goods on his Democratic rival Joe Biden. But they’re risking making their target too narrow and moving too fast.

abstract: The president’s accusations turn reality on its head and the media should say so.
snippet: The president’s accusations turn reality on its head and the media should say so.
lead_paragraph: On Sept. 24, 2015, Geoffrey Pyatt, then the American ambassador to Ukraine, spoke in Odessa about the scourge of corruption. It was about a year and a half after what is sometimes called the Revolution of Dignity, when Ukrainians overthrew the kleptocratic, Russian-aligned regime of Viktor Yanukovych. The country was trying to move in a more liberal, European direction. Corruption, said Pyatt, threatened to hold the new Ukraine back.

headline_main: Send Us Your Money or the Kitten Gets It

abstract: Why do they hate her? It’s mainly about their egos.
snippet: Why do they hate her? It’s mainly about their egos.
lead_paragraph: Remember when pundits used to argue that Elizabeth Warren wasn’t likable enough to be president? It was always a lazy take, with a strong element of sexism. And it looks ridiculous now, watching Warren on the campaign trail. Never mind whether she’s someone you’d like to have a beer with, she’s definitely someone thousands of people want to take selfies with.
